# Jarvis secrets — copy this file into your Jarvis data directory as `.env`:
#
#   cp .env.example ~/jarvis/.env        # or  $JARVIS_HOME/.env
#
# Jarvis loads `<data-dir>/.env` on startup (Node 22+ native, no dependency),
# so your secrets live next to your data (config.yaml, tasks.db) — outside this
# code repo. `.env` is gitignored; this `.env.example` is the committed template.
# Every value is optional; Jarvis also reads the process environment.
#
# Note: JARVIS_HOME is NOT read from here — it's the variable that locates this
# file. Export it (e.g. in your shell profile) for a non-default data directory;
# otherwise Jarvis uses ~/jarvis.
#
# The sections below are ordered by what you need TODAY vs. later.

# ── Active — the live GitHub connector ─────────────────────────────────────
# The only secret Jarvis actually uses today. A (fine-grained) personal access
# token with read access to the issues you track. Jarvis sends it as a Bearer
# token to the remote GitHub MCP server (https://api.githubcopilot.com/mcp/).
# Add a `github:` section to config.yaml to map repos → streams; without a token
# OR that config, Jarvis just runs folder-only.
GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN=

# ── Google Calendar (live) + Gmail (coming) ────────────────────────────────
# Used by the Calendar committed-hours provider (the Gmail connector will reuse
# them next). Create a Google OAuth *Desktop* client, paste its ID/secret here,
# then run `jarvis auth google` once. Full walkthrough:
#   docs/guides/google-calendar-setup.md
GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID=
GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET=

# ── Later (Phase 2) — Claude Agent SDK auth for execution ──────────────────
# Not used by the current read-only MVP. Needed only once Jarvis starts
# executing tasks (drafting PRs, etc.). Option ②: an API key for always-on /
# serverless runs; leave blank when running locally with a Claude subscription
# login (option ①) — same code, only the credential differs.
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=
